Through Week 10:
Baltimore's schedule and continued success make it the frontrunner to win this division.
Through Week 10 - my projections:
I've tweaked my model a little bit to account for a couple of issue that came up as the number of games left decreased.

Baltimore continues to prove they can win again against teams with star power this weekend. The Cleveland Browns defeated the Bengals this week even though Cincinnati possessed a better record. The trend shows that Baltimore is moving toward the top of the conference as we approach the midpoint of the season. The Steelers are not mathematically out of the running, but their problems at the QB position present a significant obstacle to winning games.

First, I'm a Bengal's fan. But they have the best QB (Joe Burrow) and an upgraded offensive line. They've also held their opponents to the fewest number of points in the Division. Recent Super Bowl experience for the players and coaches are helpful as well.

Among the four AFC North Teams, the Baltimore Ravens have the most balanced strengths and weaknesses. Additionally, they have a deeper bench of reserve players than the other teams of the Division.
Ravens 14-4

I'm using the weighted average of the past and current season winrate to determine the probability distribution for the number of wins at the end of the season using Poisson. Then I'm taking random values from such distribution and simulating 500 seasons to determine the likelihood of each team to win the division.
There are a lot more questions than answers after last weekend.

My initial forecast comes purely from a base rate estimation. I started by analyzing the probability distribution of winrate change from one year to the next and found that 2/3 of the times each team remains within +/- 20% of the winrate of the previous year.

The Ravens have been one of the best teams in the NFL in the past couple of years, and they were off to a good start last season until the roster was derailed by injuries. It would be unprecedented for them to suffer such poor injury luck in two successive seasons, so it is safe to say that their star veterans will be back and playing well again. Add in their new star rookie Kyle Hamilton, and the Ravens will be a dominant force again under John Harbaugh's excellent coaching. The Bengals will surely be strong again, but they are likely to suffer a super bowl hangover, as usually happens. The duo of Jamarr Chase and Joe Burrow still gives them a strong chance despite the loss of several defensive starters. Without starting quarterback Deshaun Watson, who is suspended for 11 games, the Browns will struggle. The Steelers are easily the worst team in the division, heading into a rebuild behind famous darft-bust Mitchell Trubisky at quarterback.
its either the bengals or ravens, but im feeling the bengals
